<DOC><DOCNO> AP890120-0296 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-20-89 1817EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-20 0486</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0505</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Falls for Second Day, Gold Rises</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar fell Friday for a second day ascentral banks again intervened in foreign exchange markets to put acap on the U.S. currency's climb.   Meanwhile, gold prices benefited from the dollar's decline.Republic National Bank reported a bid of $408 for a troy ounce ofgold as of 4 p.m. EST, up $4.40 from late Thursday.   Friday's dollar trading ``was a continuation of yesterday'strend,'' said Robert Ryan, a senior foreign exchange trader withIrving Trust Co.   The central banks of several nations, including the West GermanBundesbank, the Bank of England and the Bank of France, sold dollarsFriday, as they did on Thursday.   ``We've been buying, buying, buying since Dec. 1 ... and finallythe central banks forced some profit-taking,'' Ryan said.   Richard Witten, vice president for foreign exchange at Goldman,Sachs andamp; Co., said the dollar moved up when President Bush referredto the federal budget deficit in his inaugural address, but fellback when Bush offered no specifics for closing the gap.   Trading was light, dealers said.   Ryan said activity on Monday and Tuesday would give an indicationof whether the dollar will continue to soar.   In London, one British pound cost $1.7670 late Friday, moreexpensive for buyers than Thursday's $1.7615. In later New Yorktrading, the pound rose to $1.7765 from $1.7650.   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with lateThursday's prices, included: 1.8365 West German marks, down from1.85475; 1.5600 Swiss francs, down from 1.5775; 6.25975 Frenchfrancs, down from 6.3225; 1,346.125 Italian lire, down from1,359.40; and 1.18935 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18725.   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared withThursday's late rates, included: 1.8425 West German marks, down from1.8672; 1.5665 Swiss francs, down from 1.5805; 6.2715 French francs,down from 6.3315; 2.080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1060; 1,351.75Italian lire, down from 1,368.50; and 1.1868 Canadian dollars, downfrom 1.1890.   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar fell to 128.05 Japanese yen from129.20 Thursday. In London late Friday the dollar traded at 128.15yen, and in New York, it fell to 127.675 yen from late Thursday's128.655.   Gold prices rose as the dollar declined, and also in response togains in the silver market, said Stephen Platt, a metals analystwith Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold rose to $408.50 atroy ounce from $403.60 late Thursday.   The closing bid in London was $405.25 a troy ounce, up from$402.50. The Zurich close was $404.85, up from $403.40, and in HongKong, gold closed at $406.09 a troy ounce, up from $403.83.   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.05 a troy ounce, upfrom $5.97. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, silver rose to$6.183 a troy ounce from late Thursday's $5.976.</TEXT></DOC>